      "retweet": {
        "id": "2021053720222433720",
        "text": "In 1920, Mises dropped an intellectual atom bomb on socialism with a simple question: \"How do you know what anything costs without market prices?\" \n\nWhile Soviet planners were drowning in millions of arbitrary calculations, trying to set prices for everything from bread to bulldozers by committee, Mises had already proven it impossible. As Rothbard later quipped: \"Socialist calculation is like trying to play chess blindfolded while your opponent keeps moving the board.\"\n\nToday's central bankers face the same delusion, believing they can calculate the \"correct\" interest rate for an entire economy. The result? The same chaos Soviet planners created, just with better marketing.",
